---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Advanced Placement">

<div class="space-y-6">

  <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Advanced Placement</h1>
    <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm mb-4">College Board AP Program · Grades 10–12</p>
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
      Advanced Placement courses are university-level classes taught in high school. Students who
      write the AP exam in May and score well (typically 3–5 out of 5) may earn university credit —
      saving tuition and accelerating their degree. AP credentials are widely recognized by Canadian
      universities, making them a compelling option for ambitious BC students.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">

    <!-- AP Mathematics -->
    <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 border-t-4 border-t-blue-600 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-800 mb-5">AP Mathematics</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">

        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-3">Grade 10</p>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Precalculus</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">A rigorous bridge into university mathematics — functions, rates of change, and modelling. Introduced by College Board in 2022–23.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-3">Grade 11</p>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Calculus AB</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">Limits, derivatives, and integrals — equivalent to a first-semester university calculus course. The foundation of quantitative science.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Statistics</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">Data collection, probability, inference, and interpretation. In an age of misinformation, statistical literacy is a superpower.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-3">Grade 12</p>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Calculus BC</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">Extends AB with sequences, series, parametric equations, and polar coordinates. Equivalent to two semesters of university calculus. Newton and Leibniz would both approve.</p>
            </li>
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Statistics</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">Also well suited to Grade 12 — pairs naturally with data science, economics, or any field where evidence-based reasoning matters.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- AP Computer Science -->
    <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 border-t-4 border-t-blue-600 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-800 mb-5">AP Computer Science</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">

        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-3">Grade 10 – 11</p>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Computer Science Principles</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">A broad, accessible introduction to CS: algorithms, the internet, data, and the social impact of computing. No prior programming experience required — and no excuses not to try it.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-3">Grade 11 – 12</p>
          <ul class="space-y-4">
            <li class="pl-3 border-l-2 border-blue-200">
              <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 text-sm">AP Computer Science A</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-0.5">Object-oriented programming in Java: classes, data structures, algorithms, and software design. The course that separates programmers from software engineers.</p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 p-4 mt-2">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-slate-700 mb-1">A note on AP in BC</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">
            AP courses are a US College Board program, but many BC schools offer them alongside the provincial curriculum.
            Scores of 4 or 5 are typically accepted for credit at UBC, SFU, UVic, and most Canadian universities.
            Check individual university calendars for current credit transfer policies.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

</div>

</Layout>
